The paper deals with building recommender systems from count data, which is a common problem in machine learning and information retrieval. The use of Poisson Factorization and its variants is also a well-established technique in recommendation systems. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also deals with the challenges of sparse and over-dispersed data, which are common in recommendation systems, and proposes an adaptive algorithm, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper's focus on combinatorics and its use of discrete data could also make it relevant to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence).
